{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504422"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2329"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2329"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.55,0.05,0.14,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51512"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2329"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36813"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"405"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13350"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43126"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51512"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing pain in his left knee. The pain is now beginning to interfere with his job as a carpenter. He has no significant medical history but admits to a poor diet. He does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 84/min, blood pressure 124/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His BMI is 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The only abnormal finding on examination is some swelling and tenderness on pressure over the left patella, with no overlying erythema or break in skin integrity. There is a full range of movement of his knee.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management in addition to analgesia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Knee brace","Knee rest","Oral prednisone","Ultrasound-guided aspiration","Avoidance of high-purine foods"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history and examination are consistent with prepatellar bursitis, which commonly presents in patients who expose the knee to recurrent microtrauma through prolonged kneeling (such as carpenters). This is typically a self-limiting condition that improves with simple measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKnee rest\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management in addition to analgesia. Avoidance of aggravating activities, particularly kneeling, allows the inflamed bursa to heal. Simple analgesia, such as non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), can help manage pain and reduce inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eknee brace\u003C/strong\u003E can help support and stabilise the knee during the healing process, but it is not as essential as rest in the initial management of prepatellar bursitis. It may be considered as an adjunct to rest if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisone\u003C/strong\u003E can be used in patients with a contraindication to NSAIDs or in severe cases that do not respond to initial conservative measures. However, it is not the first-line management option for uncomplicated prepatellar bursitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound-guided aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered if the aspirate is needed to exclude differentials such as septic arthritis or crystal arthropathy. However, it is not typically required in straightforward cases of prepatellar bursitis and carries a small risk of iatrogenic infection of the bursa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoidance of high-purine foods\u003C/strong\u003E would be helpful in reducing gout recurrence, not prepatellar bursitis. While the patient\u0027s poor diet and obesity are noted, dietary modifications are not the immediate priority in managing his knee pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to rest and analgesia, patient education about the condition and its causes is important. The patient should be advised on ways to protect his knees at work, such as using knee pads or avoiding prolonged kneeling. Weight loss should also be encouraged as a long-term measure to reduce stress on the knees and prevent recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Avoidance of aggravating activities and simple analgesia is the first-line treatment option in prepatellar bursitis.","Prepatellar bursitis commonly presents in patients who expose the knee to recurrent microtrauma through prolonged kneeling, such as carpenters."],"references":["Khodaee M. Common Superficial Bursitis. Am Fam Physician 2017; 95:224-31. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2017/0215/p224.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36813"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2329"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36813","links":{"self":"